Documentation.name: UML 2.0 Testing Profile Technology
Documentation.notes: Result of the cooperation of Sparxsystem and Fraunhofer Fokus

Stereotype.name: TestComponent
Stereotype.notes: A test component is a structured classifier participating in test behaviors. A test component is commonly an active class with a set of ports and interfaces. Test components are used to specify test cases as interactions between a number of test components.

Stereotype.name: TestContext
Stereotype.notes: A structured classifier acting as a grouping mechanism for a set of cases. The composite structure of a test context is reffered to as test configuration. The classifier behavior of a test context is used for test control.

Constraint.name: A test context must contain exactly one property realizing the Arbiter interface.
A test context must contain exactly one property realizing the Scheduler interface.

Stereotype.name: SUT
Stereotype.notes: The SUT stereotype is applied to one or more properties of a classifier to specify that they constitute the system under test. The features and behavior of the SUT is given entirely by the type of the property to which the stereotype is applied.

Stereotype.name: TestObjective
Stereotype.notes: A dependency used to specify the objectives of a test case or test context. A test case or test context can have any number of objectives and an objective can be realized by any number of test cases or test contexts.

Constraint.name: The client of a test objective must be a named element with a test case or test context stereotype applied.

Stereotype.name: TestCase
Stereotype.notes: A test case is a behavioral feature or behavior specifying tests. A test case specifies how a set of test components interact with a SUT to realize a test objective to return a verdict value.

Constraint.name: The tipe of the return result parameter of a test case must be Verdict.
A test case stereotype can not be applied both to a behavior and its specification.
If a test case stereotype is applied to an operation, the featuring classifier must have test context stereotype applied.
If a test case stereotype is applied to a behavior, the context of the behavior must have the test context stereotype applied.

Stereotype.name: Default
Stereotype.notes: A default is a behavior used to handle unexpected or exceptional messages or events on one test component.

Stereotype.name: DefaultApplication
Stereotype.notes: A default application is a dependency used to apply a default behavior to a unit of testing on a test component.

Constraint.name: The default application relates a default to a unit of test behavior. That unit of test behavior must be one of the following: Package, Classifier, Behavior, InteractionFragment, State, Region or Activity
The multiplicity of clientdependency is restricted to [0..1]

Stereotype.name: ValidationAction
Stereotype.notes: Validation actions are used to set verdicts in test behaviors by calling the setVerdict operation on the arbiter.

Constraint.name: The operation of the action must be the setVerdict operation from the arbiter interface.
The target of the action must refer to a classifier realizing the arbiter interface.
The argument of the action must be a expression evaluating to a Verdict literal.
Validation actions can only be used in test cases i.e. a behavior where the test case stereotype is applied to the behavior or its specification.

Stereotype.name: LogAction
Stereotype.notes: A log action is used to log entities during execution for further analysis. The logged entities can be simple strings, complete diagrams, instance values or any other entity of interest.

Stereotype.name: FinishAction
Stereotype.notes: A finish action is an action that determines thet the test component will finish its execution of the test case immediately. This does not mean that the test component is terminated.

Constraint.name: The client of a test log application must be a named element with a test case or test context stereotype applied.
The supplier of a test log must be a named element with a test log stereotype applied.

Stereotype.name: CodingRule
Stereotype.notes: A coding rule specifies how values are encoded/ or decoded. Coding rules are defined outside the Testing Profile and reffered to within Testing Profile specifications.

Stereotype.name: DataPool
Stereotype.notes: The data pool stereotype extends a classifier or property to specify a container for explicit values or data partitions that are used by test contexts or test cases. A data pool provides an explicit means for associating data values for repeated tests and equivalence classes that can be used to defined abstract data sets for test evaluation.

Constraint.name: A data pool stereotype classifier can only be referenced by a test context or test component.
A data pool stereotyped property can only be applied to aproperty associated connected with a test component within the context of a test context stereotyped classifier.
A datapool stereotyped classifier cannot be associated with both a test context and a test component.

Stereotype.name: DataPartition
Stereotype.notes: The data partition stereotypes extends a classifier to specify a container for a set of values. These data sets are used as abstract equivalence classes during test context and test case evaluation.

Constraint.name: A data partition stereotyped classifier can only be associated with a data pool or another data partition.

Stereotype.name: DataSelector
Stereotype.notes: The data selector stereotype extends an operation to allow the implementation of different data selection strategies.

Constraint.name: If a data selector stereotype is applied to an operation, the featuring classifier must have either a data pool or data partition stereotype applied.

Stereotype.name: TimeOutMessage
Stereotype.notes: Extends Message. A TimeOutMessage is generated by a timer when it expires. The timeout message is sent to the active class which owns the timer.

Stereotype.name: TimeOutAction
Stereotype.notes: A timeout is enabled by a timer when it expires. An activity having the TimeOutAction as input condition occurs, when the timeout is enabled (and when all further input conditions are satisfied).

Stereotype.name: StartTimerAction
Stereotype.notes: An action used to start a timer.

Constraint.name: The operation of the action must be the start operation of the Timer interface.
The target of the action must refer to a classifier realizing the Timer interface.
The argument of the action must be a Time value.

Stereotype.name: StopTimerAction
Stereotype.notes: An action used to stop a timer. Stops the timer if it is running, does nothing otherwise.

Constraint.name: The operation of the action must be the stop operation of the Timer interface.
The target of the action must refer to a classifier realizing the timer interface.

Stereotype.name: ReadTimerAction
Stereotype.notes: An action used to read a timer to obtain the expiration time of a timer.

Constraint.name: The operation action must be the read operation from the Timer interface.
The target of the action must refer to a classifier realizing the Timer interface.
The type of the result must be Time.

Stereotype.name: TimerRunningAction
Stereotype.notes: An action used to check if a timer is currently running or not. Returns a boolean value, true if the timer is running, false otherwise.

Constraint.name: The structural feature of the action must be the isrunning attribute of the Timer interface.
The type of the result must be boolean.
The target of the action must refer to a classifier realizing the Timer interface.

Stereotype.name: GetTimezoneAction
Stereotype.notes: An action to dinamically retrieve the current timezone of a test component.

Constraint.name: The type of the structural feature of the action must be Timezone.
The type of the result must be Timezone.

Stereotype.name: SetTimezoneAction
Stereotype.notes: An action to dynamically set the timezone of a test component.

Constraint.name: The type of the structural feature of the action must be Timezone.
The value must be a Timezone value.

Stereotype.name: TimeOut
Stereotype.notes: A TimeOut is generated by a timer when it expires and may trigger an associated behavior, e.g. a transition in a statemachine.
